\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Too High the Son}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2A passionate drama persuing flight\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 Written by Stephen Bain (in collabotaration with F. Herv\'8e & T. Spite)\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Direction\tab Under Lili\'d5s Balcony\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Set design\tab S. Marriott Lloyd\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Lights       \tab Paul O\'d5Brien\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Costumes\tab N.Smiley -  Ma\'95t\'8e H.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Music        \tab F.Herv\'8e   S.Bain\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab T.Spite\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Actors\tab 3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Duration\tab 80 mins\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Premi\'8fre\tab City Gallery \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab Wellington NZ\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab 4 Sept 1996}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 Created from a simple set and  an economy of props, Too High the Son is a stylised piece with a grand dynamic. Treated as a contmporary myth, it explores the quest for individuality and the achievements of \'d4men and women of research\'d5.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Too High the Son}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  is inspired by the life of pioneer aviator Richard Pearse who flew for the first time in 1903 from his isolated farm in Otago, New Zealand. The legend insinuates that he arrived ahead of the Wright brothers in the conquest for the skies. Irrefutably a sel}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 f-taught genius, his work was ignored by his rural turn-of-the-century community, obliged to the demands of colonialism.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Following the relationship of three characters during the summer of 1903, Richard Pearse, his brother Warne (a farmer and inveterate tennis player), and Marie Garance (a young French immigrant school teacher), the story reveals the determination, despite f}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 ailures, of the three idealists infatuated by freedom and their struggle against uncompromising local puritanism.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2The world is so big... immense... then in one split second it doesn\'d5t seem so big anymore\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 National Tour Subventioned by Creative New Zealand\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Press\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 NZ Herald 6 May 1998}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2Surreal and real at the same time, Too High the Son juxtaposes images of breathtaking beauty. Dance and theatre flow seamlessly into one another in this multi-disciplinary work, creating a new language, a kind of visual poetry. Yet for all its abstract ch}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 arm, \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Too High the Son is never pretentious or inaccessible.  It is ultimately about three people and their dreams,  a tale told with warmth, intimacy and humor. \'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 NZ Listener 20 June 1998}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  \'d2... A breathtaking combination of wit, imagination and physical bravura.... \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 The key is simplicity of image. One gesture, one pose, one object symbolises all.  \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Too High the Son is something very special, a fantasia brimming with such invention, freshness and charm that it would be a worthy ambassador for New Zealand \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 on any stage in the world. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 It is like being handed a boarding pass to the future.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Evening Post 6 Sept \'d496 }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2At no time does the performance ever lose its flight of theatrical imagination.\'d3 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Capital Times 9 Sept \'d496}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2Packed with everything inventive performance should be.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Dominion 6 Sept \'d496 }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2The production is elegant in its strenght and simplicity. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 It defies categorisation, except perhaps as exploration and cultivation of myth.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 LA CHAMBRE D\'d5AMOUR}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2A short story of an infinite love in a finite time\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Written by  \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1  S. Bain & F.Herv\'8e\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Direction - Design -  Multimedia images -  Music\:\tab \tab S.Bain & F.Herv\'8e\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Lights       \tab Martyn Roberts\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Actors\tab 2\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Duration\tab 70 mins\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Premi\'8fre\tab Bats Theatre\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab Wellington\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab 2 Oct 1996\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 La Chambre d\'d5Amour takes its name from a large black rock where two lovers, surprised by the rising tide, drowned.This multimedia play reinterprates a medieval legend from the Basque French country-side through different perspective\'d5s of time.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Combining projected images (slides, 16mm film, video) with live performance, the story is told through an episodic series of spaces playing with imbalance... a pair of swings, a staircase, an open balcony, a giant aquarium... the actors play above the ever}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  present void.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2 SUN\:  Ah well, they must die then...     MOON\: That\'d5s life!\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Ella and Louis have no other choice than to hide their love for each other from view. They discover the ideal place for their meetings, a chamber under open sky in the heart of a rock, only accessible at low tide. One day never-the-less, conviced that thei}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 r love will be stronger than time, they are caught by the rising sea and drown together. From the evolution of the rock that forced an erosion just large enough to allow a man and a woman to enter, to a Kafkaesque bank of information where data of figures }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 and codes are checked and verified, the story crosses time and space to reveal the invisible reasons for this tragedy. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Commissioned by STAB Multimedia Festival, in association with Bats Theatre and Creative NZ\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Press\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 City Voice 10 Oct \'d496}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 A simple tragic tale }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 about two lovers and their clandestine meeting on a rock between tides }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 becomes a multi-dimensional exploration through space and time in Bain and Herve\'d5s innovative production }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 La chambre d\'d5Amour. Bain and Herv\'8e tell the story from different realities with fluidity and ease. Their personal repertoire and readiness to explore and experiment to their very limit is very evident. }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 They don\'d5t \'d4milk\'d5 dramatic highlights, instead moving on to each new idea, keeping the audience intently focussed on the story}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 - after all, time and tide are against them.  The performance is part of the STAB season of plays with a theme of art and technology. This array of visual imagery doesn\'d5t distract from a dynamic performance.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Dominion 4 Oct 1996}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2It is quite beautiful, obeying to its own logic and interconnections.  The audience has its attention drawn to every part of the theatre in Herv\'8e and Bain\'d5s original and inventive use of the space\'d3\tab \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Capital Times 12 Oct 1996}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2Structured like a giant poem, or a set of ha\'95kus, there is}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  a beautiful lyrical sensibility and some astonishing theatrical devices. That \'d4relish\'d5 is some of the most beautiful image-making you\'d5ll see this year, and fulfilling the experimental tag that the STAB season is there for. Images are screened to the side,}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  above and beyond the audience and film is screeen through a water tank,  in which they swim underwater.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 THE EXCHANGE\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2The price of freedom in the race of one day \'d2\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 by Paul Claudel\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Translation and Adaptation \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 F.Herv\'8e & S.Bain}
