\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 THE ABATTOIR\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2The epic tale of a modern art work\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Written by\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 France Herv\'8e\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 (Dialogue  F.Herv\'8e & S.Bain)\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 The play - a surrealabsurdist comedy - questions the role of Art in our communities.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Direction\tab F.Herv\'8e & S.Bain\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Set\tab Tony De Goldi\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Lights       \tab Martyn Roberts\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Music       \tab Jeff Henderson\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Costumes\tab Nic Smiley\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Actors\tab 9\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Duration\tab 130 mins\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Premi\'8fre\tab BATS Th\'8e\'89tre \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab Wellington NZ\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab  29 Oct 1998\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 The Abattoir recounts the escape of an art work aptly named Wild Horse, which rampages irascible through the labyrinth-like museum, threatening to destroy not only the building but society itself.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 An upheaval of events implicate each of the characters into the dilemna, revealing a satirical world where the works of art defy their creators and cultural institutions are focussed on image and profit.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2.....and I thought I could be a masterpiece one day, if I put my mind to it.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 In conjunction with the play was a multimedia installation has been placed in the foyer of the theatre and open to the public. In response to a letter -  artists an general public were invited to decide the outcome for the wild horse - a number of artists }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 nationally and internationally expressed in the form of e-mails, letters,  poemes, music, audio montage, painting, engraving and videos.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Commissioned by  STAB Multimedia Festival, in association with Bats Theatre and Creative New Zealand}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 Press\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Theatre News,  Summer 98 - 99}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2A very New Zealand topic with universal implications is given the French surrealistic-absurdist treatment and its both funny and thought-provoking. The contemporary relevance is undeniable - in the land of the three million dollar millstone, Te Papa Museu}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 m, that threatens to capsize Wellington into its harbour. Under Lili\'d5s Balcony questions other theatres too. Next to this, conventional theatre looks like a Museum, with nicely constructed works on the wall, threatened with laughter by the Abattoir.\'d3\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab }
{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Capital Times, 4 Nov 98}
{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 The play is billed as humour, fantasy, social comment, which is true- you can sink into the glorious imagery.\'d3\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 City Voice, 5 Nov 98 }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab }
{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 The Abattoir has a deliciousness of language rarely seen in the capitals theatres.  A mature play by the styley and sophisticated Under Lili\'d5s Balcony, carried by a grade A group of actors.\'d3 \tab \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab \tab \tab \tab }
{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Illusions, Autumn 1999}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2What was powerful and refreshing throughout the performance was the tireless choreographic invention of the production.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 Une pi\'8fce philosophique}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  which would demand that an audience begin to consider what art is, how it is made, how it is housed and presented, and to what ends. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 The only verdict possible for the consensus at the heart of the new Museum was that the horse be shot; thus confirming one way in which our present political moment, in thrall to the imperative of commodification, reinterprets Joseph Goebbels notorious dic}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 tum, whenever I hear the word culture, I reach for my revolver.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1  ON OFF\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2On the Edge of Change\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1  Collective creation by Under Lili\'d5s Balcony\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Writing -  Direction -  Design\tab \tab F.Herv\'8e, S.Bain\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Lights - Video      \tab \tab Matt  D\'d5Herville\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Music           \tab Jeff Henderson \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Actor\tab Gentiane Lupi\tab \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Duration\tab 20 mins\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Presented for the first time at Studio 77 (FACTORY) for the Wellington Fringe Festival 1999, as the first part of \'d2The Tower Under the Sky\'d3.}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 The Child is separated between the idea of living within the security of her Island, governed by a lighthouse but where imagination is given freedom of expression, and that which joins the greater world where the beacon has no place, where neither time, no}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 r space nor people have precise limits. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 Does growing up signify more than \'d4On\'d5 and \'d4Off\'d5?\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 On Off is a choreographic monologue, inspired by a text written in 1876 by Annie Bell Hobbs, the daughter of a lighthouse keeper.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 When it was first published in a childrens magazine, the poignant recount of her life on the miniscule Boon Island - lost in the middle of the ocean with only room enough for two houses and a lighthouse -  it moved the public so deeply that they demanded  }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 all families subjected to these conditions be returned to the mainland.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 I\'d5m not afraid because I\'d5m on my own\tab Is darkness really the same everywhere?}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Commissioned by Wellington International Fringe Festival and FACTORY, VUW}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Package, 2-8 April 1999}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2Writings are instrumental in the move to make lighthouses mechanically operated. Shockingly poignant the material is performed with childish innocence and grace.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Dominion, 23 Feb 99}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2The audience is perched on a high walkway above the side of a lighthouse watching Gentiane Lupi  on a table on which she writhes and pounds in frustration at her confinement.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 City Voice, 25 Feb 1999}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2A manic dance of a mind grown beyond the limits of its surrounds.\'d3 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 THE TOWER UNDER \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 THE SKY\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2A Treatment of Deconstruction \'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 Written & directed by\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1  F.Herv\'8e & S.Bain\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 (From a story written by F.Herv\'8e)\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Design\tab S. Marriott Lloyd\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Lights - Video     \tab  \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab Matt  D\'d5Herville\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Music\tab Jeff Henderson\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab F.Herv\'8e & S.Bain\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1  Film\tab Lala Rolls \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Actors\tab 4\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Duration\tab 90 mins\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Premi\'8fre\tab Studio 77 VUW  \tab Wellington NZ\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \tab 22 Fev 1999\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 The Tower Under the Sky is the result of an 8 week residency at the department of English, Theatre & Film, Victoria University of Wellington. Under the wings of FACTORY - a theatrical research programme directed by John Downie - Under Lili\'d5s Balcony focuss}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 ed on the investigation of \'d4framing action and the study of cinematic techniques towards their adaptation for the stage\'d5.}
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1  \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 On the night of a storm, a sailor saves a young woman close to the point of death from the ocean, and finds refuge in a lighthouse where two lovers have organised their final rendez-vous. Through this opposition and the impossibility of communication, the }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 four characters discover a common acceptance of the solitude that awaits them\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Presented in the form of a tryptic, under the title }
{\plain\i\f20\fs24\cf1 A treatment of Deconstruction}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1   - the piece offers three formats of the same story\: a choreographic quartet, a short film, and a multi-media play. It contains text in English, Japonese, French and invented language. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 KAZU\:\tab I hope she will forgive me. \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 ELISE\:\tab Forgive you what?\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 KAZU\:\tab I didn\'d5t search for anyone else.\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Commissioned by  Wellington International Fringe Festival and FACTORY\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Press\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Evening Post, 23 Feb 99}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2 Assured, inventive and technically sophisticated.  For once theatre the claim that a show is \'d2 a multimedia event\'d3 is true, and the Tower Under the Sky, succeeds with each media is uses.\'d3\tab }
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 The Dominion, 22 Feb 99}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Stephen Bain and France Herv\'8e continue to demonstrate their commitment to explore theatrical limits, using not only text and movement, but lighting, sound and music. It is mesmerising and fascinating.}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 City Voice 25 Feb 99}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2}
{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 Stylised and sumptuous with an impressive set as well as imaginative staging and choreography.\'d3\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \par }
\pard\ql{\plain\b\f20\fs24\cf1 International Theatre Performance Research Magazine, Spring 2000\par }
\pard\ql{\plain\f20\fs24\cf1 \'d2Way down in the Pacific, Under Lili\'d5s Balcony has been re-introducing the terms of such propositions with elegance, modesty, and an increasing sophistication of means.\'d3\par }
